# React UI performance patterns

## Component boundaries

- Split UI into small components only when it reduces re-renders or complexity.
- Keep "section" components (`Hero`, `ProblemSection`, `SolutionSection`, `DemoSection`, `CTASection`, `Footer`) mostly presentational.
- Put side-effects / IO (API calls, Supabase queries, html2canvas) into dedicated hooks or service modules under `src/`.

## State & rendering

- Prefer a single source of truth:
  - `DemoSection` should own its demo state; avoid duplicating derived state.
- Memoize only when it matters:
  - Use `useMemo`/`useCallback` for props passed to memoized children or heavy computations.
- Avoid inline `style={{ ... }}` objects in hot paths; extract to constants unless the values truly change.

## Motion / animation

- Use `motion/react` (already in project) consistently.
- Keep `AnimatePresence` scopes narrow. Don’t wrap large trees if only a small sub-tree needs enter/exit.
- Prefer `viewport={{ once: true }}` to reduce repeated animation work unless the design requires it.

## Assets & icons

- Use SVG paths from `src/imports/*.ts` only when necessary; otherwise prefer `lucide-react` for consistency.
- Ensure `viewBox` matches icon path coordinates to avoid sizing/blur issues:
  - If `viewBox="0 0 20 20"`, use 20x20 paths.
  - If `viewBox="0 0 24 24"`, use 24x24 paths.

